_*b \approx _{\mathcal {B} x} b witnessing the unit law that pushforward along the reflexivity datum \mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\colon  x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} x is the identity function.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
A reflexive graph \mathcal {A} is called univalent when for all x:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
 the type \mathchoice {\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\textstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}}{\scriptscriptstyle \sum _{
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen y:
 \mathopen {}\left \lvert \mathcal {A}\right \rvert \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
}} x\approx _{\mathcal {A}} y is a proposition, or (equivalently), is contractible with centre 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,\mathsf {rx}_{\mathcal {A}}{x}\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We shall refer to a univalent reflexive graph as a path object.
